                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d551">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">723.2515/3274: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Peru</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Moore</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Paraphrase]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Lima</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1929-03-02T23:00:00-05:00"
                            >March 2, 1929—11 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received March 3—4:10 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>26. Your 18, March 2, 6 p.m. Your understanding of the matter is correct. The
                    greatest distance is 10 kilometers and the smallest is 30 meters. This
                    suggestion was handed to the Chilean Ambassador on Thursday, February 28.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Moore</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
